******
[2]
Date: Tue 21 Jan 2014
Source: The Korea Times [in Korean, trans. & summ., edited]
http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2014/01/116_150193.html


Several more poultry farms in North Jeolla Province reported cases of suspected bird flu Tuesday [21 Jan 2014], but the government said that doesn't mean the disease is spreading to other regions beyond the already-designated "danger zone."

The Ministry of Agriculture, Food and Rural Affairs lifted a "lockdown" order Monday night [20 Jan 2014] that had banned the movement of poultry, farmers and workers within South and North Jeolla provinces and Gwangju [Gyeonggi province].

One duck farm near the west coast in Gochang, North Jeolla Province, reported the deaths of ducks with likely symptoms of avian influenza Tuesday morning [21 Jan 2014]. It is 19 kilometers [12 mi] away from the farm that reported the 1st outbreak.

The agriculture ministry, however, found that it is run by the same owner of the farm in Buan who had reported the 2nd outbreak of bird flu. Having tracked movements of his feed-carrying trucks, the government concluded that the disease was only transmitted from one farm to the other.

Around noon, another farm in Jeongeup in North Jeolla Province reported suspected symptoms of bird flu -- the 1st case to take place outside Gochang and Buan.

The agriculture ministry said that although it took place in a different administrative district, the farm in Jeongeup is within the "danger zone" -- an area within 3 kilometers [2 mi] from bird flu-struck farms that the government regularly inspects. It won't consider it as a new outbreak or spread of the disease.

Within the danger zones in or near Gochang and Buan, the government found 6 poultry farms with suspected symptoms of bird flu and one was confirmed to be infected with highly pathogenic virus. Ducks in all 6 farms were culled.

In the meantime, tens of thousands of Baikal teals have left the Dongrim Reservoir where some 60 of them were found dead, infected with the H5N8 strain of avian influenza. These species of migratory birds are suspected to have spread the disease as they flew over the farms.

The teals that left Dongrim are believed to have moved to Geumgang Lake in Gunsan, North Jeolla Province, with the number of the birds increasing from some 50 000 to 250 000, according to the local migratory bird observatory.

On Tuesday [21 Jan 2014], however, the number shrank to some 100 000 as food was covered by snow and became scarce.

There is also the fear that ducks from the bird-flu struck farm in Buan have been supplied to a slaughterhouse in Naju, South Jeolla Province, according to Yonhap News Agency. The government hasn't confirmed yet if the slaughtered ducks have been distributed to consumers.

Kwon Jae-han, the ministry official in charge of livestock policy, told a press briefing that the most important point in quarantine efforts is to prevent the flow of any source of infection, such as excrement of migratory birds, into poultry farms.

The AI virus has an incubation period of up to 3 weeks. "This means avian influenza could break out at any time throughout the winter season when the disease is most rampant," he said

[A picture in the article shows a vehicle spraying disinfectant at Eulsukdo, a mid-river island serving as a wintering ground for migratory birds, in the Nakdong River, which courses through Busan, South Korea's 2nd largest metropolis after Seoul].

[Byline: Kim Da-ye]

